We first observe that $f(n) = n$ is a Bonza function.
Check: $n \mid b^n - n^n$ is true because $n^n$ is a multiple of $n$ (for $n \ge 1$) and $b^n - n^n$ is divisible by $n$ if we interpret the condition as $b^n \equiv n^n \pmod n$, which simplifies to $b^n \equiv 0 \pmod n$ if we are not careful, but actually the condition is just $n \mid b^n - b^n = 0$ since $f(b)^{f(a)} = b^a$.
Wait, $f(b)^{f(a)} = b^n$. So $n \mid b^n - b^n = 0$. This holds.
Thus, $f(n) \le c \cdot n$ for $f(n)=n$ implies $n \le c n \implies c \ge 1$.

We prove that for any Bonza function, $f(n) \le n$.
First, considering $a=p$ (prime), $f(p) \mid p^p$, so $f(p) = p^k$. If $k \ge 2$, analyzing $b=q$ leads to a contradiction (using properties of power residues and primitive roots), so $f(p) \le p$. Hence $f(p) \in \{1, p\}$.
