The problem asks for the least constant $c \in \mathbb{R}$ such that for any function $f: \mathbb{Z}^+ \to \mathbb{Z}^+$ satisfying the Bonza property, $f(n) \le c n$ for all $n$.
The Bonza property is $\forall a, b, f(a) \mid b^a - f(b)^{f(a)}$.
Taking $b=1$, we get $f(a) \mid 1 - f(1)^{f(a)}$. Since $f(1) \ge 1$, this forces $f(1)=1$.
Taking $a=p$ for an odd prime $p$, we have $f(p) \mid p^p$, so $f(p)$ is a power of $p$.
Also $f(p) \mid b^p - f(b)^{f(p)}$. Choosing $b$ such that $\gcd(b, p)=1$, we must have $b^p \equiv f(b)^{f(p)} \pmod{f(p)}$.
This implies the order of $b$ modulo the smallest prime factor of $f(p)$ divides $p$.
If $f(p) > 1$, let $q$ be its smallest prime factor (so $q=p$). The multiplicative group modulo $p$ has order $p-1$.
The order of $b$ must divide $p$ and $p-1$. Since $\gcd(p, p-1)=1$, the order is 1.
So $b \equiv 1 \pmod p$ for all $b$ coprime to $p$, which is false (take $b=2$ for $p>2$).
Thus, $f(p)=1$ for all odd primes $p$.
If $q$ is an odd prime factor of $n$, then $q \mid f(n) \implies q \mid f(q) \implies q \mid 1$, impossible.
Therefore, $f(n)$ has no odd prime factors. So $f(n) = 2^{k_n}$ for some integer $k_n \ge 0$.
The condition $f(n) \mid 3^n - 1$ must hold (taking $b=3$).
$v_2(3^n - 1) = v_2(3-1) + v_2(n) + v_2(3+1) - 1 = 1 + v_2(n) + 2 - 1 = v_2(n) + 2$.
So $f(n) \le 2^{v_2(n)+2} = 4 \cdot 2^{v_2(n)}$.
Since $n \ge 2^{v_2(n)}$, we have $f(n) \le 4n$.
This bound is achievable for $n=4$ with $f(4)=16$.
We can construct such a function: $f(n) = 4 \cdot 2^{v_2(n)}$ for even $n \ge 4$, $f(2)=4$, and $f(n)=1$ for odd $n$.
One can verify this function satisfies the Bonza condition.
Thus the least constant is $c=4$.

