The least constant is $c=4$.

The upper bound $f(n) \le 4n$ holds for any Bonza function.
First, for any odd prime $p$, $f(p)=1$. If $f(p) > 1$, then $p \mid f(p)$. Applying the condition with $a=p, b=2$ gives $f(p) \mid 2^p - f(2)^{f(p)}$. Since $f(2) \mid 4$, $f(2) \in \{1, 2, 4\}$, so $f(2)$ is a power of 2. Thus $2^p \equiv 2^{k f(p)} \pmod p$. By Fermat's Little Theorem, $2 \equiv 2^{k f(p)}$. This implies the order of $2$ modulo $p$ divides $k f(p) - 1$. But the order also divides $p-1$. Since $\gcd(k p^m - 1, p-1) = 1$, the order is 1, so $2 \equiv 1 \pmod p$, impossible. Thus $f(p)=1$.
It follows that for any $n$, $f(n)$ has no odd prime factors, so $f(n)$ is a power of 2.
Using $b=3$ and $f(3)=1$, we have $f(n) \mid 3^n - 1$. The valuation $v_2(3^n - 1) = v_2(n) + 2$. Thus $f(n) \le 2^{v_2(n)+2} = 4 \cdot 2^{v_2(n)} \le 4n$.

The lower bound is achieved by $f(n) = 2^{v_2(n)+2}$ for $v_2(n) \ge 2$, $f(n)=4$ for $v_2(n)=1$, and $f(n)=1$ for odd $n$. One checks this is Bonza and $f(4)=16=4(4)$.

